[thinking] **Exploring Android class loading**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m trying to figure out if I can add a correct dependency for an older Android version and exclude the newer one for tests. There's this issue about class loading - can I sacrifice Android64 and use a custom class loader to load classes a second time? It seems like I shouldn’t drop dynamic coverage and that I need to consider metadata generation on the JVM. It’s a bit complex, but I'm considering ways to navigate dynamic class loading effectively.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Analyzing test execution and class loading**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I think tests should run under Native by default to catch unsupported dynamic class loading. Maybe I can exercise Android32 through a public API path and build classes via a custom class loader with dependency jars. I need this custom loader to handle Kafka shaded protobuf and libcore.io.Memory. It’s tricky because I have to decide between older and newer android-all dependencies. Using reflection for calling parseFrom from the test class may be necessary, but it feels complex, especially with metadata collection. I’m not sure if direct reflection can work either!
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Examining dependency management in Gradle**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I need to find the right dependency jars in Gradle at runtime. For the test, I can use `System.getProperty("java.class.path")` to filter out the kafka-clients jar and the older android jar. I think I need to include the older android-all as a build dependency, but the custom child-first class loader can only load certain classes. It seems like the test's message class should be in the child loader, but the existing structure complicates things, especially if I want to define a separate source package for tests!
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Investigating classloading issues**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm looking into a custom classloader for native images, specifically for loading classes from the classpath after a build. It seems like it might not be supported, so I need to catch an UnsupportedFeatureError. In the JVM, the agent collects errors, but in a native context, I'll need to catch and assert the error myself. I'll also check if NativeImageSupport is imported and whether this dependency is available with the TCK. Now, it’s time to search!
[thinking] 
